Svelte and Solid both need an accessor when query inputs are reactive, so the query is rebuilt when inputs change.

```ts
// Svelte
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  projectId ? app.todos.where({ projectId }) : undefined,
);
```

```ts
// Solid
const [todos] = useAll(() => ({
  query: projectId() ? app.todos.where({ projectId: projectId() }) : undefined,
}));
```

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear locally together after the batch commits.

Use `db.transaction(...)` for two writes that must stay staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together.

```ts
const batched = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
```

```ts
const tx = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await tx.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

For upload, require remote edge durability in the helper call and in the parent insert flow:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Profile photo",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

That means success is reported only after all file parts and the parent row have reached `edge`. For download when local chunks may be incomplete, read with a tier and handle the two failure states separately:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // file row not visible
  } else if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // missing-part, part-size-mismatch, or invalid-file-record
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
```

Use `loadFileAsStream(...)` instead if you want sequential consumption instead of a full `Blob`.

Delete in dependency order while inherited permissions still exist: load the `uploads` row, load its `files` row, delete every referenced `file_parts` row, delete the `files` row, then delete the parent `uploads` row last.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}
db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the parent first; that can remove the inherited delete authorization needed to clean up the file and chunks.
